[If bluebloods won't pay high prices for racehorses anymore, ]1 [who
will? ]2

[Breeders are betting on the common folk. ]3

[The Thoroughbred Owners and Breeders Association, a Lexington,
Ky.-based trade group, has launched "seminars" for "potential
investors" at race tracks around the country. ]4 [The group, ]5 [which
has held half a dozen seminars so far, ]6 [also is considering
promotional videos and perhaps a pitch to Wall Street investment
bankers. ]7

["People in this business have been insulated," ]8 [says Josh Pons, a
horse breeder from Bel Air, Md. ]9 ["But the real future of this game
is in a number of people ]10 [owning a few horses." ]11

[At the Laurel race track, the breeders are romancing people like Tim
Hulings, a beer packaging plant worker. ]12 [Right now, Mr. Hulings is
waving his racing program, ]13 [cheering for Karnak on the Nile, a
sleek thoroughbred ]14 [galloping down the home stretch. ]15

[Mr. Hulings gloats ]16 [that he sold all his stocks ]17 [a week
before the market plummeted 190 points on Oct. 13, ]18 [and he is
using the money ]19 [to help buy a 45-acre horse farm. ]20 ["Just
imagine how exciting that would be ]21 [if that's your horse," ]22 [he
